{{distinguish|text=[[Tanglish]] (the interlanguage of Tamil) or [[Tinglish]] (the interlanguage of Thai)}} '''Tenglish''' ({{lang-te|తెంగ్లిష్}}), a [[portmanteau]] of the words [[Telugu language|Telugu]] and [[English language|English]], is the combined usage of Telugu and English in one sentence.
==Distribution== This form of [[code-switching]] is more commonly seen in urban and suburban centers of [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Telangana]], but is slowly spreading into rural and remote areas via television and word of mouth.<ref name=":0" /> Many speakers do not realize that they are incorporating English words into Telugu sentences or Telugu words into English sentences.<ref name=":0" /> For example, instead of saying ''dhanyavadhamulu'' for "thank you", most people say ''chala thanks'' literally translating to "a lot of thanks." <ref name=":0" /> This type of Telugu speaking is slowly growing outside of cities like [[Hyderabad]], [[Vizag]], [[Vijayawada]], [[Khammam]] ,[[Guntur]] and [[Warangal]]. As English becomes more and more prevalent, it can be seen in small towns, villages, and even rural areas.<ref name=":0" />
It may have a slight influence by the Indian language of Dakhani.
With its growing popularity, Tenglish is being used to publish news online.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Young-Hans/2017-01-16/Tenglish-Telugu-plus-English/273782|title=1|last=|first=|date=|website=Tenglish News|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> The advent of cable television and its pervasive growth has seen the masses exposed to a wide variety of programming from across the world.<ref name=":0" /> Another factor contributing to the spread of Tenglish is the popularity of [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Tollywood]] films and TV channels.<ref name=":0" /> Tenglish also appears in Indian crossword puzzles, such as those in the Telugu paper ''[[Sakshi (newspaper)|Sakshi]]''.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/crosswords/crossword-blog/2012/dec/06/crossword-blog-cryptics-india|title=Crossword blog: cryptics in India|first=Alan|last=Connor|date=6 December 2012|website=the Guardian|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref>
